# Go Conventions

Target: Go 1.24+. Backend services, CLIs, APIs.

## Errors

- Wrap: `fmt.Errorf("op: %w", err)`. Never discard errors.
- Sentinel: `var ErrFoo = errors.New("foo")`. Check with `errors.Is`.
- No panic in library code.

## Concurrency

- Context first parameter: `func F(ctx context.Context, ...)`.
- Every goroutine has explicit exit condition (context cancel, channel close, WaitGroup).
- Use `errgroup` for parallel work with error collection.
- Mutex embedded as first field in owning struct.

## HTTP

- Client and server always have explicit timeouts set.
- Validate all inputs at handler entry.
- Filesystem paths from user input go through `os.OpenRoot`/`*os.Root`, not manual sanitization.

## Stdlib & Idioms

- Prefer `slices`/`maps`/`cmp` and `min`/`max`/`clear` over hand-rolled helpers; `for i := range n` for counts.
- Expose iteration as `iter.Seq`/`iter.Seq2` (Go 1.23+); `json:",omitzero"` over `omitempty` for zero values.
- Declare tool deps in `go.mod` (`go tool`), not `tools.go`. Modernize with `golangci-lint`'s `modernize` (or `go fix` on Go 1.26+).

## Testing

- Table-driven tests: `[]struct{ name, input, want }`.
- Subtests with `t.Run`. Parallel with `t.Parallel()` where safe.
- No real network in unit tests — use interfaces and fakes.
- Benchmarks use `for b.Loop()` (Go 1.24); test time-dependent concurrency with `testing/synctest` (Go 1.25+), not `time.Sleep`.

## Naming

- Receivers: short, consistent, not `self`/`this`.
- Context variable: always `ctx`.
- Interfaces at point of use (consumer package).
- Avoid `util/`, `common/`, `helpers/` package names.

## Project Layout

```
cmd/<name>/main.go
internal/
pkg/        (only if library)
```
